==Old English==

===Etymology===
From West Germanic: cognate with Old Saxon ''mīþan'' (Dutch [[mijden]]), Old High German [[midan|mīdan]] (German [[meiden]]).

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/'mi:ðan/}}

===Verb===
{{Unicode|'''mīþan'''}} (class I strong: ''3 singular present'' {{Unicode|'''[[miþþ|mīþþ]]'''}}, ''3 singular preterite'' {{Unicode|'''[[maþ|māþ]]'''}}, ''3 plural preterite'' '''[[miþon]]''', ''past participle'' (ġe)'''[[miþen]]''')
# to [[hide]], [[conceal]]
#:''Cyriacus hygerune ne mað to Gode cleopode.''  Cyriacus did not hide his mind's secret, but cried out to God.

